{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592688"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:18:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:18:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15276"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15276"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.36,0.09,0.23,0.14,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7967"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69021"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7967","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7967"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15276"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54478"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8746"},{"type":"tags","id":"9982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19388"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69021"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EIn coeliac disease, gliadin (a component of gluten) interacts with intestinal epithelial cells, triggering an immune response.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following interleukins is produced by intestinal epithelial cells in response to gliadin exposure?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Interleukin-2","Interleukin-13","Interleukin-6","Interleukin-15","Interleukin-4"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn coeliac disease, when gliadin contacts and activates intestinal epithelial cells, they produce \u003Cstrong\u003Einterleukin-15\u003C/strong\u003E. This cytokine specifically activates CD8+ intraepithelial lymphocytes, which contribute to intestinal tissue damage and inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterleukin-2\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily produced by activated T cells, not intestinal epithelial cells\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterleukin-13\u003C/strong\u003E is mainly produced by T helper 2 cells and is involved in allergic responses\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterleukin-6\u003C/strong\u003E is produced by various cells during acute phase responses and inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterleukin-4\u003C/strong\u003E is produced by T helper 2 cells and is involved in B cell responses\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe production of interleukin-15 by intestinal epithelial cells is a crucial early step in the pathogenesis of coeliac disease, leading to the activation of immune cells that cause tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Intestinal epithelial cells produce interleukin-15 when activated by gliadin in coeliac disease","Interleukin-15 activates CD8+ intraepithelial lymphocytes as part of the immune response in coeliac disease","The interaction between gliadin and intestinal epithelial cells is a key initiating step in coeliac disease pathogenesis"],"references":["DuPont HL. Persistent Diarrhea: A Clinical Review. JAMA. 2016 Jun 28;315(24):2712-23. doi: 10.1001/jama.2016.7833. PMID: 27357241","Nemeth V, Pfleghaar N. Diarrhea. [Updated 2022 Nov 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448082/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Kaiser L, Surawicz CM. Infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. Best Pract Res Clin Gastroenterol. 2012 Oct;26(5):563-71. doi: 10.1016/j.bpg.2012.11.001. PMID: 23384802","Vives-Pi M, Takasawa S, Pujol-Autonell I, Planas R, Cabre E, Ojanguren I, Montraveta M, Santos AL, Ruiz-Ortiz E. Biomarkers for diagnosis and monitoring of celiac disease. J Clin Gastroenterol. 2013 Apr;47(4):308-13. doi: 10.1097/MCG.0b013e31827874e3. PMID: 23388848."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54478"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15276"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54478"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T20:34:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T20:36:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7967"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69021"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading